Investigation Overview¶

My goal is to see which pokemon are stronger than others and if there are characteristics that attribute to their strength. While the dataset has multiple columns to gather information on I focused on the pokemon's battle stats which are composed of their, "HP", "ATK", "DEF", "Special_ATK" and "Special_DEF. I also viewed the pokemon's weight to see if that played a factor in the pokemon's attack points.

My key insights are:

The relationship between a pokemon's weight and their strength

The correlation between The pokemon's generation and if they are a dualtype pokemon.

The pokemon's HP and their attack points(ATK and Special_ATK).

Dataset Overview¶

We have a dataset full of various pokemon of different types. There are over 800 different Pokemon with an array of different battle stats. This slideshow is going to give you a better idea as to what types of the pokemon are the strongest and weakest, and which top individual Pokemon were the strongest.

Pokemons attributes that are available for statistical analysis is their individual Attack, Defense, Special Attack, Special Defense, Speed, and Health points. The pokemon also posses either one or two poketypes. They can also be sorted into which generation they belong to.

(Visualization 1)¶

In this visualization I wanted to show how the weight of a pokemon can impact their attack points if at all. I chose 4 different poketypes that compose an array of pokemon of different weights.

g.map(plt.scatter, 'Weight','ATK')

x_ticks = [0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 10, 30, 100, 300, 1000]
g.set(xticks = x_ticks, xticklabels = x_ticks)
g.add_legend()

(Visualization 2)¶

The pokemon have different generation classes that they belong to. I wanted to compare how their Generational class compares to the Pokemon themselves. I have created a column called SingleType and that columns state whether a pokemon is a single or a dual type by an output of True or False. I used the battle stats as the y variables to show how either graph is impacted by it.

In [25]:
#create a violinplot to depict a combination of boxplot and kernel density estimate.
g = sb.PairGrid(pk,
                 x_vars=["Generation_ID","SingleType"],
                 y_vars=["ATK","DEF","Special_ATK", "Special_DEF"],
                 aspect=.85, size=6)
g.map(sb.violinplot,palette="pastel")
plt.show()

(Visualization 3)¶

My final graph shows how a pokemons's attack points and special attack points correlate with one another. Per this visualization I don't think The HP of a pokemon makes an impact on their attack power.
